                            <strong>Benevolent AI drug discovery paper at ICLR 2018: my open review</h3></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Open Review is a platform for reviewing papers submitted at some AI conferences. Anyone can throw his opinion about any paper. Some reviews are very crusty, a kind of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rotten_Tomatoes" target="_self">Rotten Tomatoes</a> for machine learning research.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">I came across a paper about my favourite topic, generative models in drug discovery. The paper is called: <em>“Exploring Deep Recurrent Models with Reinforcement Learning for Molecule Design”</em>. I couldn’t resist to post my review.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><div class="sketchy"><a href="https://openreview.net/forum?id=HkcTe-bR-"><h2 style="color:blueviolet; font-family:Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size:25px;">Exploring Deep Recurrent Models with Reinforcement Learning for...</h2><h3 style="color:rgb(45, 34, 54); font-family:Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size:20px;">The design of small molecules with bespoke properties is of central importance to drug discovery. However significant…</h3><p>openreview.net</p></a></div></div></div></div></section><br><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">The paper is written by Nathan Brown and his team (Daniel Neil, Marwin Segler, Laura Guasch, Mohamed Ahmed, Dean Plumbley, Matthew Sellwood), from BenevolentAI, a startup in AI for drug discovery. According to their <a href="http://www.benevolent.ai" target="_self">website</a>:</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content7 cid-ttbhFZC4Ql" id="content7-8" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
